Airplane Crashes since 1908

Brian Wang

8/2/2017

I obtained this data set via Kaggle at https://www.kaggle.com/saurograndi/airplane-crashes-since-1908. I’m going to explore it with some light visualizations in order to get an understanding of which airlines had the most crashes / were the least safe from 1908-2009, which is the latest year in the dataset.

library(tidyverse)
library(readr)
library(DT)
library(data.table)

Load data

airplanes <- read_csv("/Users/brianwang/Desktop/r/data-projects/airplane-crashes/airplane_crashes_1908.csv", col_types = cols(
  `Date` = col_date(format="%m/%d/%Y"),
  Time = col_character(),
  Location = col_character(),
  Operator = col_character(),
  `Flight #` = col_character(),
  Route = col_character(),
  Type = col_character(),
  Registration = col_character(),
  `cn/In` = col_character(),
  Aboard = col_integer(),
  Fatalities = col_integer(),
  Ground = col_integer()
))

A summary of the columns in this dataset:

  • Date - date of the crash
  • Time - time of the crash
  • Location - location of the crash
  • Operator - airline operator
  • Flight # - flight number
  • Route - aircraft route
  • Type - type of aircraft
  • Registration - aircraft registration identifier - see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aircraft_registration
  • cn/In - aircraft construction number?
  • `Aboard - number of passengers aboard
  • `Fatalities - number of passenger fatalities
  • Ground - So I’m actually not sure what this variable is.
  • Summary - summary description of incident

I noticed when I was importing the data that there were a few observations that had extra characters in the Time column, so I’m going to clean this data and then convert the Time column to a time variable.

airplanes$Time[3537] <- '09:43'
airplanes$Time[3268] <- '14:20'
airplanes$Time <- gsub("['\\.]",":",airplanes$Time)
airplanes$Time <- parse_time(gsub("c[:]*","",airplanes$Time),format="%R")

Total crashes, passengers aboard, fatalities and survivors per year

counts <- airplanes %>%
  group_by(Year=year(Date)) %>%
  summarise(Count = n())
p1 <- counts %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Count)) + 
  geom_col(fill="#0b9f93") +
  geom_col(data = subset(counts,Count==max(Count)), fill="yellow", color="black") +
  geom_text(data = subset(counts,Count==max(Count)), aes(label=Count), vjust=-0.5, size = 3) +
  ggtitle("Crashes per year, 1908 - 2009")
aboard <- airplanes %>%
  group_by(Year=year(Date)) %>%
  summarise(Count = sum(Aboard, na.rm=TRUE))
p2 <- aboard %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Count)) + 
  geom_col(fill="#8b3f83") +
  geom_col(data = subset(aboard,Count==max(Count)), fill="yellow", color="black") +
  geom_text(data = subset(aboard,Count==max(Count)), aes(label=Count), vjust=-0.5, size = 3) +
  ggtitle("Aboard passengers per year, 1908 - 2009")
fatalities <- airplanes %>%
  group_by(Year=year(Date)) %>%
  summarise(Count = sum(Fatalities, na.rm=TRUE))
p3 <- fatalities %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Count)) + 
  geom_col(fill="#0b9fc3") +
  geom_col(data = subset(fatalities,Count==max(Count)), fill="yellow", color="black") +
  geom_text(data = subset(fatalities,Count==max(Count)), aes(label=Count), vjust=-0.5, size = 3) +
  ggtitle("Fatalities per year, 1908 - 2009")
airplanes$survivors <- airplanes$Aboard - airplanes$Fatalities
survivors <- airplanes %>%
  group_by(Year = year(Date)) %>%
  summarise(Count = sum(survivors, na.rm=TRUE))
p4 <- survivors %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Count)) + 
  geom_col(fill="#0bbfc3") +
  geom_col(data = subset(survivors,Count==max(Count)), fill="yellow", color="black") +
  geom_text(data = subset(survivors,Count==max(Count)), aes(label=Count), vjust=-0.5, size = 3) +
  ggtitle("Survivors per year, 1908 - 2009")
multiplot(p1, p2, p3, p4, cols = 2, layout = matrix(c(1,2,4,1,3,4), nrow=3))

What airline has had the most crashes since 1908?

airplanes %>%
  group_by(Operator) %>%
  summarise("Count" = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(Count)) %>% datatable()
airplanes %>%
  group_by(Operator) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>% arrange(desc(Count)) %>%
  filter(Count >= 10) %>% na.omit() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Operator,Count), y=Count)) + 
  geom_col(fill="#922415") +
  geom_text(aes(label=Count), size = 1, hjust = 1.4, color = "#FFFFFF") +
  ggtitle("Airlines with most crashes since 1908") +
  labs(x="Airline", y="Count") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 4)) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,1)) +
  coord_flip()

  • Aeroflot has had the most crashes by far. It’s kinda crazy. It’s had more crashes than the U.S. military? I also looked it up and it’s still an airline today? Aeroflot is the “flag carrier and the largest airline of the Russian federation”. Oh man. When did these crashes happen? I’m going to take the top ten airlines and plot their crashes per year since 1908 to see if there are any trends exhibited. I’m hoping Aeroflot gets better over time…
topten <- (airplanes %>%
  group_by(Operator) %>%
  summarise("Count" = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(Count)))$Operator[1:10]
toptenbyyear <- airplanes %>%
  filter(Operator %in% topten) %>%
  group_by(Year = year(Date), Operator) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>% arrange(desc(Count))
toptenbyyear %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Count)) + geom_line() + facet_wrap(~Operator)

There’s a few things that we can note from this chart:

  • We observe that there are a quite a few airlines that have no crashes for a significant number of years in the period 1908-2009.
  • The U.S. Army Air Forces (1947) and Deutsche Lufthansa (1945) both ceased to exist shortly after World War II - we can assume that most of these crashes are war-related.
  • The China National Aviation Corporation ceased to exist after 1949, a side effect of the Chinese Civil War, when the managing director of CNAC defected to Communist-controlled China (while being pursued by KMT fighter planes!)
  • Pan Am World Airways went bankrupt in 1991 and was sold to United Airlines, Delta Airlines, and Lufthansa, among other airlines.
  • Air Taxi doesn’t seem to be a airline company - I wonder if this is just a combined label for air taxi operators.
  • The remaining in the top ten are either currently operating airlines or military.
  • Answering our previous question: it looks the 1970s were particularly rough for Aeroflot.

From this, we also note that it might not be accurate to judge the “safety” of an airline operator by the aggregate number of crashes it’s had. Instead, let’s try to compute a “crashes-per-year” metric, which is the total number of crashes normalized by the number of the years the airline was in operation. We also note that we don’t know if an airline had a crash both in its inaugural year and last year, so we will have to confirm the lifespan of the airline operator by outside sources. We can do this for the top ten airlines.

Crashes / fatalities per year, normalized by airline operator lifetime

toptenbyoperator <-
  airplanes %>%
  filter(Operator %in% topten) %>%
  group_by(Operator) %>%
  summarise(Count = n(), Fatalities = sum(Fatalities, na.rm=TRUE))
toptenbyoperator$opyears <-
  c(2009-1923,
    2009-1933,
    NA, # Air Taxi
    2009-1936,
    1949-1929,
    1945-1926,
    2009-1947,
    1947-1941,
    1991-1927,
    2009-1926)
toptenbyoperator %>%
  mutate("Crashes Per Year" = Count / opyears, "Fatalities Per Year" = Fatalities / opyears) %>%
  select(1:3, 5:6) %>% datatable() %>% formatRound(4:5, 2)
  • Overall, all the military airlines have a higher average number of crashes per year than the passenger airlines.
  • We note that even though the US Army Air Forces have a low overall count of crashes, they have the most crashes pe year by far. Deustche Lufthansa, the German air force during WWII, has the second highest average number of crashes per year (half of the US Army Air Forces number!). The German air force crashed a lot less - and had a lot less fatalities on average per year (178 compared to 20)!
  • United, American, and Air France have the best average records, averaging less than 1 crash per year. Pan American also had a good record before it went bankrupt.
  • Don’t fly Aeroflot! It has by far the highest average number of fatalities and crashes per year among passenger airlines. By the graph of crashes it seems to have had a pretty good record recently (as recent as 2009?) but I don’t know.
